,-0.00374219,-0.02034159,0.04664613,-0.06454088,-0.00353199,0.05426212,0.00481697,-0.00513016,-0.02211234,0.02335371,-0.00264236,0.03747296,-0.00599703,-0.01311343,-0.02298949,0.02501459,0.00867085,-0.08351979,0.01402560,-0.03681223,-0.01070103,0.01239968,-0.09372934,-0.05557794,-0.03562298,-0.04791961,0.01339835,0.01295967,-0.07748611,-0.04659093,-0.03133095,-0.05146368,0.01174180,0.03518072,0.00590005,-0.07732145,0.03286336,0.01068500,0.04104188,0.11437994,0.02638446,0.04278277]',E'Getting up and running\n\nEven with the `CatsController` fully defined, Nest doesn''t yet know about it and won''t automatically create an instance of the class.\n\nControllers must always be part of a module, which is why we include the `controllers` array within the `@Module()` decorator. Since we haven’t defined any other modules apart from the root `AppModule`, we’ll use it to register the `CatsController`:\n\n```typescript\n@@filename(app.module)\nimport { Module } from ''@nestjs/common'';\nimport { CatsController } from ''./cats/cats.controller'';\n\n@Module({\n  controllers: [CatsController],\n})\nexport class AppModule {}\n```\n\nWe attached the metadata to the module class using the `@Module()` decorator, and now Nest can easily determine which controllers need to be mounted.','{"source": "nestjs", "version": "11", "language": "typescript", "title": "Controllers", "section_title": "controllers", "url": "https://github.com/nestjs/docs.nestjs.com/blob/master/content/controllers.md", "topics": "nestjs,typescript,controllers", "categories": "web,typescript,rest,enterprise"}');
