5,0.18746366,0.08660404,-0.01900933,0.07629809,0.01520643,0.04790701,0.00537137,-0.03074621,-0.03104306,-0.01831653,0.03796712,-0.00074406,0.08963288,-0.07932045,0.01721372,-0.02039337,0.05648216,-0.01049938,-0.08028654,0.02008065,0.00990388,0.01888699,0.04889100,-0.01056972,-0.01454458,-0.01095687,0.00276911,0.06644350,-0.05127211,-0.02000622,-0.00528125,-0.04106670,0.00932934,-0.00030710,0.03164788,-0.05475986,-0.05075388,0.00760361,0.06451681,0.04449729,0.05387066,0.00463660,-0.00598852]',E'Putting it all together\n\nWhen a user with insufficient privileges requests an endpoint, Nest automatically returns the following response:\n\n```typescript\n{\n  "statusCode": 403,\n  "message": "Forbidden resource",\n  "error": "Forbidden"\n}\n```\n\nNote that behind the scenes, when a guard returns `false`, the framework throws a `ForbiddenException`. If you want to return a different error response, you should throw your own specific exception. For example:\n\n```typescript\nthrow new UnauthorizedException();\n```','{"source": "nestjs", "version": "11", "language": "typescript", "title": "Guards", "section_title": "guards", "url": "https://github.com/nestjs/docs.nestjs.com/blob/master/content/guards.md", "topics": "nestjs,typescript,guards", "categories": "web,typescript,rest,enterprise"}');
