,0.20424294,0.06657326,-0.01182064,-0.01154122,-0.03513044,0.03871850,0.03365089,0.01240408,0.03257866,-0.00677527,0.05789242,0.01061402,0.10258007,-0.05909685,-0.07471654,-0.00989331,0.02103324,-0.00203054,-0.06507751,0.02465112,-0.02311832,-0.00471864,0.02200253,-0.04391592,-0.02960375,-0.06525828,0.01550894,0.00404001,0.02493405,-0.00200645,0.02254776,-0.05453505,0.00126291,0.04144808,0.07583036,-0.04138257,-0.06339179,0.05691907,0.04224484,0.04162431,0.06274241,0.06517832,-0.01248240]',E'Built-in pipes\n\nNest comes with several pipes available out-of-the-box:\n\n- `ValidationPipe`\n- `ParseIntPipe`\n- `ParseFloatPipe`\n- `ParseBoolPipe`\n- `ParseArrayPipe`\n- `ParseUUIDPipe`\n- `ParseEnumPipe`\n- `DefaultValuePipe`\n- `ParseFilePipe`\n- `ParseDatePipe`\n\nThey''re exported from the `@nestjs/common` package.\n\nLet''s take a quick look at using `ParseIntPipe`. This is an example of the **transformation** use case, where the pipe ensures that a method handler parameter is converted to a JavaScript integer (or throws an exception if the conversion fails). Later in this chapter, we''ll show a simple custom implementation for a `ParseIntPipe`. The example techniques below also apply to the other built-in transformation pipes (`ParseBoolPipe`, `ParseFloatPipe`, `ParseEnumPipe`, `ParseArrayPipe`, `ParseDatePipe`, and `ParseUUIDPipe`, which we''ll refer to as the `Parse*` pipes in this chapter).','{"source": "nestjs", "version": "11", "language": "typescript", "title": "Pipes", "section_title": "pipes", "url": "https://github.com/nestjs/docs.nestjs.com/blob/master/content/pipes.md", "topics": "nestjs,typescript,pipes", "categories": "web,typescript,rest,enterprise"}');
